DO $$
DECLARE
    v_course_id UUID;
    v_module_id UUID;
BEGIN
    SELECT id INTO v_course_id FROM courses WHERE title ILIKE '%Vibe Coding%' LIMIT 1;
    IF v_course_id IS NULL THEN RAISE EXCEPTION 'Vibe Coding course not found'; END IF;
    
    SELECT id INTO v_module_id FROM modules WHERE course_id = v_course_id AND ordering = 4 LIMIT 1;
    IF v_module_id IS NULL THEN RAISE EXCEPTION 'Module 4 not found'; END IF;
    
    RAISE NOTICE 'ðŸ“š Expanding Vibe Coding Module 4 (All 5 Lessons)...';
    
    -- LESSON 11: UI / Frontend AI
    UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="lesson-content"><h2>UI / Frontend AI Tools</h2><h3>Building Beautiful Interfaces with AI</h3><p>Frontend developmentâ€”creating the visual interfaces users interact withâ€”has been transformed by AI tools. You can now describe what you want and watch it come to life, without memorizing CSS properties or wrestling with layout issues.</p><p>This lesson explores the best AI tools for frontend development, when to use each one, and how to get professional results.</p><h3>The Frontend AI Landscape</h3><p>Frontend AI tools fall into several categories: Component Generators (create individual UI components), Full Page Builders (generate complete pages), Design-to-Code Tools (convert designs to code), Styling Assistants (help with CSS and styling), and Framework-Specific Tools (specialized for React, Vue, etc.).</p><h3>Top Frontend AI Tools</h3><h4>1. v0 by Vercel</h4><p><strong>What it does:</strong> Generates React components and full pages from text descriptions.</p><p><strong>Best for:</strong> React/Next.js projects, modern web apps, component libraries</p><p><strong>Strengths:</strong> Beautiful, production-ready code. Uses modern React patterns. Integrates with Tailwind CSS. Great for shadcn/ui components.</p><p><strong>Example use:</strong> "Create a pricing page with three tiers, each showing features, price, and a CTA button. Use a modern, clean design with gradients."</p><h4>2. Bolt.new</h4><p><strong>What it does:</strong> Generates complete web applications from descriptions.</p><p><strong>Best for:</strong> Quick prototypes, MVPs, simple web apps</p><p><strong>Strengths:</strong> Extremely fast. No setup required. Instant preview. Great for beginners.</p><p><strong>Example use:</strong> "Build a todo list app with add, complete, and delete functionality. Use a clean, minimal design."</p><h4>3. Lovable (formerly GPT Engineer)</h4><p><strong>What it does:</strong> Creates full-stack applications with beautiful UIs.</p><p><strong>Best for:</strong> Design-focused applications, SaaS products, landing pages</p><p><strong>Strengths:</strong> Exceptional design quality. Handles both frontend and backend. Iterative refinement built-in.</p><p><strong>Example use:</strong> "Create a SaaS landing page for a project management tool. Include hero section, features, pricing, and testimonials."</p><h4>4. Figma AI + Plugins</h4><p><strong>What it does:</strong> Converts Figma designs to code.</p><p><strong>Best for:</strong> Teams with designers, pixel-perfect implementations</p><p><strong>Strengths:</strong> Preserves design intent. Works with existing design workflows. Multiple export options.</p><p><strong>Example use:</strong> Design in Figma, then use plugins like "Figma to Code" or "Anima" to generate React/HTML.</p><h4>5. Framer</h4><p><strong>What it does:</strong> Visual design tool with AI-powered code generation.</p><p><strong>Best for:</strong> Marketing sites, portfolios, interactive prototypes</p><p><strong>Strengths:</strong> No-code interface with code export. Beautiful animations. Fast deployment.</p><p><strong>Example use:</strong> Design visually in Framer, add AI-generated interactions, publish or export code.</p><h3>Choosing the Right Tool</h3><p><strong>For Quick Prototypes:</strong> Use Bolt.new - fastest from idea to working prototype.</p><p><strong>For Production React Apps:</strong> Use v0 - generates clean, maintainable React code.</p><p><strong>For Beautiful Design:</strong> Use Lovable - prioritizes visual quality.</p><p><strong>For Design Handoff:</strong> Use Figma AI - maintains design fidelity.</p><p><strong>For Marketing Sites:</strong> Use Framer - optimized for content and conversion.</p><h3>Best Practices for Frontend AI</h3><h4>1. Start with Layout, Then Details</h4><p>First iteration: "Create a dashboard layout with sidebar navigation and main content area."</p><p>Second iteration: "Add a stats grid showing 4 key metrics with icons and trend indicators."</p><p>Third iteration: "Style the stats cards with subtle shadows and hover effects."</p><h4>2. Use Visual References</h4><p>Instead of describing every detail, reference existing designs: "Make it look like Stripe''s dashboard", "Use a design similar to Linear", "Style it like Notion''s interface"</p><h4>3. Specify Responsiveness Early</h4><p>"Create a responsive pricing grid that shows 3 columns on desktop, 2 on tablet, and 1 on mobile."</p><h4>4. Request Accessibility Features</h4><p>"Include proper ARIA labels, keyboard navigation, and focus states for accessibility."</p><h4>5. Iterate on Styling Separately</h4><p>Get the structure right first, then refine colors, spacing, and visual details.</p><h3>Common Frontend Patterns</h3><p><strong>Hero Sections:</strong> "Create a hero section with headline, subheadline, CTA button, and background image. Include a subtle gradient overlay."</p><p><strong>Feature Grids:</strong> "Create a 3-column feature grid. Each feature has an icon, title, and description. Use a card-based layout."</p><p><strong>Forms:</strong> "Create a contact form with name, email, message fields. Include validation and a submit button with loading state."</p><p><strong>Navigation:</strong> "Create a responsive navbar with logo, menu items, and a CTA button. Mobile menu should slide in from the side."</p><p><strong>Cards:</strong> "Create a product card showing image, title, price, and add-to-cart button. Include hover effects."</p><h3>Styling with AI</h3><p>Most frontend AI tools use Tailwind CSS or similar utility frameworks. You can guide styling with specific instructions:</p><p><strong>Colors:</strong> "Use blue (#3B82F6) as the primary color and gray (#6B7280) for text."</p><p><strong>Spacing:</strong> "Use generous spacing between sections (96px) and tight spacing within components (16px)."</p><p><strong>Typography:</strong> "Use Inter font. Headings should be bold and large (32px). Body text should be 16px with good line height (1.6)."</p><p><strong>Effects:</strong> "Add subtle shadows to cards, smooth transitions on hover, and rounded corners (8px)."</p><h3>Handling Complex Layouts</h3><p>For complex layouts, break them down modularly:</p><p>Step 1: "Create the overall page structure with header, main content, and footer."</p><p>Step 2: "In the main content area, create a two-column layout with sidebar (1/4 width) and content (3/4 width)."</p><p>Step 3: "In the sidebar, add navigation links and a search box."</p><p>Step 4: "In the content area, create a grid of article cards."</p><h3>Responsive Design with AI</h3><p>AI tools generally handle responsiveness well, but you can be explicit:</p><p>"Create a responsive layout that: Shows 4 columns on desktop (1200px+), Shows 2 columns on tablet (768px-1199px), Shows 1 column on mobile (below 768px), Hides the sidebar on mobile and shows a hamburger menu instead."</p><h3>Animation and Interaction</h3><p>Add life to your interfaces with AI-generated animations:</p><p>"Add smooth transitions: Fade in elements as they scroll into view, Smooth hover effects on buttons (scale up slightly), Page transitions when navigating, Loading skeletons while content loads."</p><h3>Dark Mode</h3><p>Many AI tools can generate dark mode automatically:</p><p>"Create this component with both light and dark mode support. Use system preference to determine which to show."</p><h3>Component Libraries</h3><p>AI tools often integrate with popular component libraries:</p><p><strong>shadcn/ui:</strong> v0 generates components using this library</p><p><strong>Material-UI:</strong> Specify "use Material-UI components"</p><p><strong>Chakra UI:</strong> Request "build with Chakra UI"</p><p><strong>Ant Design:</strong> Ask for "Ant Design components"</p><h3>Exporting and Integration</h3><p>Once you''ve generated frontend code: Copy the code to your project, Install required dependencies (usually listed by the tool), Adjust imports and paths as needed, Test in your environment, Refine with additional AI prompts if needed.</p><h3>Common Challenges and Solutions</h3><p><strong>Challenge:</strong> Generated code doesn''t match your existing style.<br><strong>Solution:</strong> Provide examples of your existing components as context.</p><p><strong>Challenge:</strong> Layout breaks on certain screen sizes.<br><strong>Solution:</strong> Test on multiple devices and request specific breakpoint fixes.</p><p><strong>Challenge:</strong> Too much or too little spacing.<br><strong>Solution:</strong> Be specific: "Reduce spacing between cards to 16px" or "Increase section padding to 64px".</p><p><strong>Challenge:</strong> Colors don''t match your brand.<br><strong>Solution:</strong> Provide exact hex codes and specify where each color should be used.</p><h3>Key Takeaways</h3><ul><li>Frontend AI tools range from <strong>component generators to full page builders</strong></li><li>Choose tools based on your needs: <strong>v0 for React, Bolt.new for speed, Lovable for design quality</strong></li><li>Start with <strong>layout, then add details</strong> iteratively</li><li>Use <strong>visual references</strong> instead of describing every detail</li><li>Specify <strong>responsiveness and accessibility</strong> early</li><li>Break down <strong>complex layouts modularly</strong></li><li>Most tools use <strong>Tailwind CSS</strong> or similar utility frameworks</li></ul><p>In the next lesson, we''ll explore Full-Stack & Auto Builders that handle both frontend and backend together.</p></div>'
    WHERE module_id = v_module_id AND ordering = 1;
    RAISE NOTICE 'âœ… Lesson 11 Complete';
    
    RAISE NOTICE 'ðŸŽ‰ Module 4 Lesson 1/5 Complete!';
    
END $$;
